comments.body:
This is the **most error-prone and indispensable** sub-lemma: the resolution is NOT simply 'the prior is improper.' Construct the explicit **proper** prior $P(A=2^k)=\tfrac13(\tfrac23)^k$, $k\ge0$, and prove:
(i) it is a probability measure (properness);
(ii) $E[Y\mid X=2^n]>2^n$ for **every** $n$ (verified: ratio $=1.1$ for $x\ge2$, $=2$ for $x=1$);
(iii) $E[X]=E[Y]=+\infty$;
(iv) consequently the law of iterated expectation $E[Y]=E_X[E[Y\mid X]]$ **fails** (both sides $\infty$ / not well-defined), so SEU does not rank switching vs. staying.
Conclusion to state: here the paradox is dissolved by **non-integrability**, a mechanism distinct from impropriety. Reference: Broome, *Analysis* 55 (1995). Without G4 the claim of a 'single resolution covering all cases' is unproven.
